<section xml:id="section-standard-form">

    <title>Standard-Form Equation</title>
    <introduction>
    <p>In this section, we will learn a line's equation in standard form. Here is a video lecture as an overview.</p>

    <figure><video youtube="SMZ7aB-FKZg" width="70%" /></figure>
    </introduction>

    <subsection>
        <title>Introduction to Standard Form Equations</title>

        <p>We have learned the following forms of a line's equation:
            <ul>
                <li>slope-intercept form <m>y=mx+b</m> and</li>
                <li>point-slope form <m>y-y_1=m(x-x_1)</m></li>
            </ul>
        In this lesson, we will learn the standard-form of a linear equation,<men xml:id="standard-form-equation">Ax+By=C</men>where <m>A, B</m> and <m>C</m> are real numbers. We will look at a scenario first.</p>

        <paragraphs>
            <title>Scenario</title>

            <p>Michael got a budget of <dollar/><m>200</m> to purchase some staplers and some markers. Each stapler costs <dollar/><m>5.00</m>, and each marker costs <dollar/><m>2.00\text{.}</m> Assume he will purchase <m>x</m> staplers and <m>y</m> markers. Write a linear equation to model the relationship between the number of staplers and markers Michael can purchase.</p>
        </paragraphs>

        <p>We will use the following table to show the cost of staplers.</p>

        <table>
            <caption>Cost of Staplers</caption>
            <tabular>
                <col halign="center" />
                <col halign="center"/>
                <row bottom="medium">
                    <cell>Number of Staplers</cell>
                    <cell>Cost (in dollars)</cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell><m>1</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>5\cdot1=5</m></cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell><m>2</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>5\cdot2=10</m></cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell><m>3</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>5\cdot3=15</m></cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell><m>4</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>5\cdot4=20</m></cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell><m>\vdots</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>\vdots</m></cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell><m>x</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>5x</m></cell>
                </row>
            </tabular>
        </table>

        <p>By the relationship in the table, we can see the cost of buying <m>x</m> staplers would be <m>5x</m> dollars. Similarly, the cost of buying <m>y</m> markers would be <m>2y</m> dollars. Assume Michael will spend all <m>200</m> dollars, we have the equation<me>5x+2y=200</me>This is a standard-form equation as in <xref ref="standard-form-equation">Equation</xref>. Next, let's graph it.</p>

        <p>The first method to graph the equation is to build a table of <m>x</m>-values and <m>y</m>-values, as in <xref ref="section-cartesian-coordinates">Section</xref>. For example, when <m>x=0</m>, we have:</p>

        <p><md>
            <mrow>5x+2y\amp=200</mrow>
            <mrow>5(0)+2y\amp=200</mrow>
            <mrow>2y\amp=200</mrow>
            <mrow>y\amp=100</mrow>
        </md></p>

        <p>By the calculation above, when <m>x=0\text{,}</m> <m>y=100\text{,}</m> implying a point on the line is <m>(0,100)\text{.}</m></p>

        <p>Next, we substitute <m>x</m> in <m>5x+2y=200</m> with other values, and we can build the following table with <m>x</m>-vlaues and <m>y</m>-values. Details are left as exercises.</p>

        <table>
            <caption>Table for <m>5x+2y=200</m></caption>
            <tabular>
                <col halign="center"/>
                <col halign="center"/>
                <col halign="center"/>
                <row bottom="medium">
                    <cell><m>x</m>-values</cell>
                    <cell><m>y</m>-values</cell>
                    <cell>Points</cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell><m>0</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>100</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>(0,100)</m></cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell><m>10</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>75</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>(10,75)</m></cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell><m>20</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>50</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>(20,50)</m></cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell><m>30</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>25</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>(30,25)</m></cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell><m>40</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>0</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>(40,0)</m></cell>
                </row>
            </tabular>
        </table>

        <p>With values in the table, we can graph the line:</p>

        <figure xml:id="graph-of-stapler-marker-problem">
            <caption>Graph of <m>5x+2y=200</m></caption>
            <image>
            <description>This is a grid with the graph of line 5x+2y=200. The following points are ploted: (0,100), (10,75), (20,50), (30,25), (40,0). A slope triangle is drawn from (0,100) to (10,100), and then to (10,75). The triangle's base is labeled "10-10=10", and its height is labeled "75-100=-25".</description>
            <latex-image-code>
            <![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}
                    \begin{axis}[
                        xlabel={number of staplers}, ylabel={number of markers},
                        xmin=-20,xmax=60,ymin=-10,ymax=120,
                        minor xtick=, minor ytick=,
                        xtick={0,10,...,50},ytick={20,40,...,100}
                    ]
                        \addplot[
                            domain = 0:40,
                            -,
                            smooth,
                            thin,
                            color = red,
                        ]{-5/2*x+100};
                        \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(0, 100)} node[above left] {$(0,100)$};;
                        \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(10, 75)} node[below left] {$(10,75)$};;
                        \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(20, 50)};
                        \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(30, 25)};
                        \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(40, 0)};
                        \addplot[guideline,->] coordinates {(0,100) (10,100) (10,75)};
                        \node at (axis cs: 5,100) [above] {$10-0=10$};
                        \node at (axis cs: 10,87.5) [right] {$75-100=-25$};
                        \node at (axis cs: 30,40) [above right, color=red] {$5x+2y=200$};
                    \end{axis}
            \end{tikzpicture}
            ]]>
            </latex-image-code>
            </image>
        </figure>

        <p>By the slope triangle, this line's slope is <m>\frac{-25}{10}=-\frac{5}{2}\text{.}</m> Note that <m>x</m>-values represent the number of staplers, and <m>y</m>-values represent the number of markers. The slope implies, each time Michael purchase <m>2</m> more staplers (worth <dollar/>10.00), he can afford <m>5</m> fewer markers (also worth <dollar/>10.00).</p>

        <p>Let's pay attention to two points on the line: its <m>x</m>-intercept and <m>y</m>-intercept.</p>

        <p><ul >
                <li>The <m>x</m>-intercept is at <m>(40,0)\text{.}</m> It implies Michael can purchase <m>40</m> staplers and no markers.</li>
                <li>The <m>y</m>-intercept is at <m>(0,100)\text{.}</m> It implies Michael can purchase <m>100</m> markers and no staplers.</li>
            </ul></p>

        <p>Since two points can determine a line's location, we could have graphed this line simply by its two intercepts. The next section is about how to graph a line by intercepts.</p>

    </subsection>

    <subsection>
        <title>Graphing Lines by Intercepts</title>

        <p>If a line is in standard form, it's often easy to graph it with its two intercepts. We will start with a video lecture, followed by an example.</p>

        <figure><video youtube="Wgpq0zO6z3o" width="70%" /></figure>

        <example xml:id="example-graph-by-intercepts">
            <statement>
                <p>Graph <m>2x-3y=-6</m> with its intercepts.</p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>To graph a line by its <m>x</m>-intercept and <m>y</m>-intercept, we first set up a table this way:</p>
                <table>
                    <caption>Intercepts of <m>2x-3y=-6</m></caption>
                    <tabular>
                        <col halign="left"/>
                        <col halign="center"/>
                        <col halign="center"/>
                        <col halign="center"/>
                        <row bottom="medium">
                            <cell/>
                            <cell><m>x</m>-value</cell>
                            <cell><m>y</m>-value</cell>
                            <cell>Intercepts</cell>
                            <cell/>
                        </row>
                        <row>
                            <cell><m>x</m>-intercept</cell>
                            <cell/>
                            <cell><m>0</m></cell>
                            <cell/>
                        </row>
                        <row>
                            <cell><m>y</m>-intercept</cell>
                            <cell><m>0</m></cell>
                            <cell/>
                            <cell/>
                        </row>
                    </tabular>
                </table>

                <p>An <m>x</m>-intercept is on the <m>x</m>-axis. It looks like <m>(1,0), (2,0), (-5,0)</m>... Its <m>y</m>-value is always <m>0\text{,}</m> which is why, for the <m>x</m>-intercept in the table, we can directly put <m>0</m> into the <m>y</m>-value cell.</p>

                <p>Similarly, a line's <m>y</m>-intercept looks like <m>(0,1), (0,2), (0,-5)</m>... Its <m>x</m>-value is always <m>0\text{,}</m> which is why, for the <m>y</m>-intercept in the table, we can directly put <m>0</m> into the <m>x</m>-value cell.</p>

                <p>Next, we calculate the line's <m>x</m>-intercept by substituting <m>y</m> in the equation with <m>0\text{:}</m><md>
                    <mrow>2x-3y\amp=-6</mrow>
                    <mrow>2x-3(0)\amp=-6</mrow>
                    <mrow>2x\amp=-6</mrow>
                    <mrow>x\amp=-3</mrow>
                </md>
                The line's <m>x</m>-intercept is <m>(-3,0)\text{.}</m></p>

                <p>Similarly, we substitute <m>x</m> in the equation with <m>0\text{:}</m><md>
                    <mrow>2x-3y\amp=-6</mrow>
                    <mrow>2(0)-3y\amp=-6</mrow>
                    <mrow>-3y\amp=-6</mrow>
                    <mrow>y\amp=2</mrow>
                </md>
                The line's <m>y</m>-intercept is <m>(0,2)</m>. Now we can fill out the table:</p>

                <table>
                    <caption>Intercepts of <m>2x-3y=-6</m></caption>
                    <tabular>
                        <col halign="left"/>
                        <col halign="center"/>
                        <col halign="center"/>
                        <col halign="center"/>
                        <row bottom="medium">
                            <cell/>
                            <cell><m>x</m>-value</cell>
                            <cell><m>y</m>-value</cell>
                            <cell>Intercepts</cell>
                        </row>
                        <row>
                            <cell><m>x</m>-intercept</cell>
                            <cell><m>-3</m></cell>
                            <cell><m>0</m></cell>
                            <cell><m>(-3,0)</m></cell>
                        </row>
                        <row>
                            <cell><m>y</m>-intercept</cell>
                            <cell><m>0</m></cell>
                            <cell><m>2</m></cell>
                            <cell><m>(0,2)</m></cell>
                        </row>
                    </tabular>
                </table>

                <p>With both intercepts' coordinates, we can graph the line:</p>

                <figure>
                    <caption>Graph of <m>2x-3y=-6</m></caption>
                    <image>
                    <description>This is a grid with the graph of line 2x-3y=-6. The following points are ploted: (0,2), (-3,0). The segment from (0,0) to (0,2) is labeled "2-0=0", and the segment from (-3,0) to (0,0) is labeled "0-(-3)=3".</description>
                    <latex-image-code>
                    <![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}
                            \begin{axis}[
                                xmin=-5,xmax=2,ymin=-1,ymax=4,
                                minor xtick=, minor ytick=,
                                xtick={-4,-3,...,1},ytick={1,2,3}
                            ]
                                \addplot[
                                    domain = -4.5:2,
                                    <->,
                                    smooth,
                                    thin,
                                    color = red,
                                ]{2/3*x+2};
                                \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(0, 2)} node[above left] {$(0,2)$};;
                                \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(-3, 0)} node[above left] {$(-3,0)$};
                                \node at (axis cs: -1.5,0) [above, color=black] {$0-(-3)=3$};
                                \node at (axis cs: 0,1) [right, color=black] {$2-0=2$};
                            \end{axis}
                    \end{tikzpicture}
                    ]]>
                    </latex-image-code>
                    </image>
                </figure>

                <p>The line, the <m>x</m>-axis and the <m>y</m>-axis form a slope triangle, and we can see the slope is:<me>\text{slope}=\frac{\Delta y}{\Delta x}=\frac{2}{3}</me></p>
            </solution>
        </example>
    </subsection>

