    <subsection>
        <title>Horizontal Lines and Vertical Lines</title>

        <p>We will start this subsection with two video lectures.</p>

        <sidebyside>
            <figure><video youtube="iSgftOjXIfw" width="70%" /></figure>
            <figure><video youtube="kdPWd_c3UXY" width="70%" /></figure>
        </sidebyside>

        <p>In <xref ref="subsection-zero-slope">Subsection</xref>, we learned that, in a time-distance graph, the slope of a line represents speed. A horizontal line's slope is <m>0\text{,}</m> because the distance doesn't change as time moves on. How do we write a horizontal line's equation?</p>

        <p>A slope-intercept form equation looks like <m>y=mx+b\text{.}</m> When the slope is <m>0</m>, we substitute <m>m</m> with <m>0\text{,}</m> and the equation becomes<me>y=b</me>This is exactly how we write a horizontal line's equation.</p>

        <p>We can also graph a horizontal line by a table of values. Let's build a table for <m>y=3\text{:}</m></p>

         <table>
            <caption>A Table of Values for <m>y=3</m></caption>
            <tabular>
                <col halign="center" />
                <col halign="center"/>
                <col halign="center"/>
                <row bottom="medium">
                    <cell><m>x</m>-values</cell>
                    <cell><m>y</m>-values</cell>
                    <cell>Points</cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell><m>-2</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>3</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>(-2,3)</m></cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell><m>-1</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>3</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>(-1,3)</m></cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell><m>0</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>3</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>(0,3)</m></cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell><m>1</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>3</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>(1,3)</m></cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell><m>2</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>3</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>(2,3)</m></cell>
                </row>
            </tabular>
        </table>

        <p>The following figure has the graph of <m>y=3</m> and some other horizontal lines.</p>

        <figure>
            <caption>Equations of Horizontal Lines</caption>
            <image>
            <description>There are a few horizontal lines, labeled y=-2.5, y=0, y=3.</description>
            <latex-image-code>
            <![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}
                    \begin{axis}[
                        xmin=-5,xmax=5,ymin=-5,ymax=5,
                        minor xtick=, minor ytick=,
                        xtick={-4,-2,...,4},ytick={-4,-2,...,4}
                    ]
                        \addplot[
                            domain = -5:5,
                            <->,
                            smooth,
                            thin,
                            color = blue,
                        ]{-2.5};
                        \node at (axis cs: -3,-2.5) [above, color=blue] {$y=-2.5$};

                        \addplot[
                            domain = -5:5,
                            <->,
                            smooth,
                            thin,
                            color = red,
                        ]{0};
                        \node at (axis cs: 1,0) [above, color=red] {$y=0$};

                        \addplot[
                            domain = -5:5,
                            <->,
                            smooth,
                            thin,
                            color = black,
                        ]{3};
                        \node at (axis cs: 3,3) [above, color=black] {$y=3$};
                        \addplot[only marks,color=black] 
                            coordinates{
                                (-2,3)
                                (-1,3)
                                (0,3)
                                (1,3)
                                (2,3)
                            };
                    \end{axis}
            \end{tikzpicture}
            ]]>
            </latex-image-code>
            </image>
        </figure>

        <p>Since the <m>x</m>-axis is a horizontal line, it has the equation: <m>y=0\text{.}</m> We use horizontal lines to model scenarios where there is no change in <m>y</m>-values, like when Emiliano stopped moving in <xref ref="subsection-zero-slope">Subsection</xref>.</p>

        <p>In <xref ref="subsection-vertical-line-slope">Subsection</xref>, we learned that a vertical line's slope is undefined, or infinitely large. Since a horizontal line's equation is in the form of <m>y=b\text{,}</m> it makes sense to write a vertical line's equation in the form of <m>x=a\text{,}</m> where <m>a</m> is a real number. Let's build a table for the line <m>x=3\text{,}</m> and then graph it.</p>

         <table>
            <caption>A Table of Values for <m>x=3</m></caption>
            <tabular>
                <col halign="center" />
                <col halign="center"/>
                <col halign="center"/>
                <row bottom="medium">
                    <cell><m>x</m>-values</cell>
                    <cell><m>y</m>-values</cell>
                    <cell>Points</cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell><m>3</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>-2</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>(3,-2)</m></cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell><m>3</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>-1</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>(3,-1)</m></cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell><m>3</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>0</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>(3,0)</m></cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell><m>3</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>1</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>(3,1)</m></cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell><m>3</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>2</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>(3,2)</m></cell>
                </row>
            </tabular>
        </table>

        <p>The following figure has the graph of <m>x=3</m> and some other vertical lines.</p>

        <figure>
            <caption>Equations of Vertical Lines</caption>
            <image>
            <description>There are a few vertical lines, labeled x=-2.5, x=0, x=3.</description>
            <latex-image-code>
            <![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}
                    \begin{axis}[
                        xmin=-5,xmax=5,ymin=-5,ymax=5,
                        minor xtick=, minor ytick=,
                        xtick={-4,-2,...,4},ytick={-4,-2,...,4}
                    ]
                        \draw[<->,blue] (axis cs: -2.5,-5) to (axis cs: -2.5,5);
                        \node at (axis cs: -2.5,3) [left, color=blue] {$x=-2.5$};

                        \draw[<->,red] (axis cs: 0,-5) to (axis cs: 0,5);
                        \node at (axis cs: 0,1) [left, color=red] {$x=0$};

                        \draw[<->,black] (axis cs: 3,-5) to (axis cs: 3,5);
                        \node at (axis cs: 3,2) [left, color=black] {$x=3$};
                        \addplot[only marks,color=black] 
                            coordinates{
                                (3,-2)
                                (3,-1)
                                (3,0)
                                (3,1)
                                (3,2)
                            };
                    \end{axis}
            \end{tikzpicture}
            ]]>
            </latex-image-code>
            </image>
        </figure>

        <p>Next, we look at an example where a vertial line is used.</p>

        <paragraphs>
            <title>Scenario</title>

            <p>Effie, Ivan and Cleo are in a race. The following graph models their distance from the starting point in the first few seconds. Find each person's distance <m>3</m> seconds into the race.</p>
        </paragraphs>

        <figure>
            <caption>Three People's Distance from the Stating Point</caption>
            <image>
            <description>This is a grid with 3 lines to model 3 people's distance from the starting line. Effie's line passes (0,0) and (3,4). This line is colored blue. Ivan's line passes (0,0) and (1,2). This line is colored red. Cleo's line passes (0,0) and (1,3). This line is colored black. A green vertical line goes from (3,-1) to (3,10). This line intersects with Effie's line at (3,4), with Ivan's line at (3,6), with Cleo's line at (3,9).</description>
            <latex-image-code>
            <![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}
                    \begin{axis}[
                        xlabel={seconds},ylabel={meters},
                        xmin=-1,xmax=6,ymin=-1,ymax=10,
                        minor ytick=,
                        minor xtick=,
                        xtick={0,1,...,5},ytick={0,1,...,9}
                    ]
                          \addplot[
                            domain = 0:6,
                            ->,
                            smooth,
                            thin,
                            color = blue,
                          ]{4/3*x};
                          \node at (axis cs: 5,7) [color = blue] {Effie};
                          \addplot[soliddot, color=blue] coordinates {(3, 4)} node[right] {(3,4)};

                          \addplot[
                            domain = 0:5,
                            ->,
                            smooth,
                            thin,
                            color = red,
                          ]{2*x};
                          \node at (axis cs: 4,8) [color = red] {Ivan};
                          \addplot[soliddot, color=red] coordinates {(3, 6)} node[right] {(3,6)};

                          \addplot[
                            domain = 0:10/3,
                            ->,
                            smooth,
                            thin,
                            color = brown,
                          ]{3*x};
                          \node at (axis cs: 2,8) [color = brown] {Cleo};
                          \addplot[soliddot, color=brown] coordinates {(3, 9)} node[right] {(3,9)};

                          \draw[color=black, <->] (axis cs: 3,-1) -- (axis cs: 3,10);
                          \node at (axis cs: 3,1) [left, color = black] {$x=3$};
                    \end{axis}
            \end{tikzpicture}
            ]]>
            </latex-image-code>
            </image>
        </figure>

        <p>The black vertial line crosses those three lines at <m>(3,4), (3,6)</m> and <m>(3,9)</m>. They imply: <m>3</m> seconds into the race, Effie was <m>4</m> meters away from the starting point, Ivan was <m>6</m> meters away, and Cleo was <m>9</m> meters away. The vertical line is used to check each line's <m>y</m>-value when <m>x=3\text{.}</m></p>

    </subsection>

